<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY DIGEST / LOCAL NEWS IN BRIEF: TUSTIN; 
</P>
<P>
TRINITY'S CROUCH ATTENDS MEETING WITH PRESIDENT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Paul F. Crouch, founder and president of Tustin-based Trinity Broadcasting 
Network, was among 16 evangelical leaders who met with President Bush on 
Tuesday. The religious leaders requested the meeting because of what one called 
a "crisis of confidence" following Bush's statements last month indicating he 
opposes tuition tax credits for parents of private school students. Bush 
assured them he still favors the tax credits, adding, however, that because of 
budget restraints he is unable to push for them now, the White House said. In 
addition to tax credits, the evangelicals and Bush also discussed their mutual 
opposition to abortion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
<GRAPHIC>
<P>
Photo, President Bush talks at the White House with, from left around table, 
Paul Crouch, president of Trinity Broadcasting; Billy Zeoli, president of 
Gospel Films, and Jerry Vines, president of the Southern Baptist Convention. 
Associated Press 
</P>
